Printree (printree.net) sent me their sample swatch book.

These are the fabrics to consider:

  1) Cotton Canvas            263.7 gram per square meter
  2) linen                    195.9 gram per square meter
  3) polycanvas polyester
  4) canvas polyester crepe   380 gram per square meter

The fabric weights are taken from
https://printree.net/bbs_detail.php?bbs_num=13&id=&tb=bbs_faq&pg=1.

1, 2, and 3 were in the swatch book.  3 was not on the fabric weight
chart.

3 is the heavyest/stiffest.

Fabric widths:

  * canvas:  43 inch
  * linen:   59 inch


They recommend uploading an image file at 200dpi resolution even
though the swatch book says its samples were printed at 300dpi.

These are the supported file types: JPEG, PNG, TIFF, or PSD.  TIFF
might be the best choice.

In the swatch book, the largest text shown was 12pt.  This seemed
quite clear on the fabrics of interest.  Our CSS file uses 0.2, 0.3
and 0.4 inch for font-size.  These are all bigger than 1/6 inch (0.167
inch) for 12 point text.


How do we layout our pages onto the fabric?

If we use CSS borders to provide the lines to cut on then all of the
space between the endge of the page and the content would be accounted
for by CSS padding.  CSS margin would just be used for the space
between the cut lines.  That includes the left edge gutter for the
binding, the top and bottom "margins", and the space between the right
edge and the "thread" holes.

CSS margin might be less relevant since what matters is how the actual
graphics anre spaces across and along the length of the fabric.

